<Document>
<name>Wild Atlantic Way — Connemara</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Wild Atlantic Way — Connemara</h2><p><i>Republic of Ireland · Galway to Westport via Clifden, Letterfrack, and Killary</i></p><p><b>Pat McCabe called it 'one of the wildest, loveliest places that I know.' Boglands, ten thousand stone walls, Ireland's only fjord.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>148 km (92 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 2 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–September (and February for empty roads)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Sheep on road, sudden squalls, narrow roads through villages, pubs that close the road</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>258</td></tr></table><hr><p>Connemara is West Galway — a region of granite, bog, and indented Atlantic coast, where Irish (Gaeilge) is still the everyday language in many villages. The Wild Atlantic Way is a 2,500 km tourism route hugging Ireland's western coast; the Connemara section is one of its showcases. Drive slowly. Stop at a pub. The stone walls — there must be ten thousand kilometres of them across these mountains — are the cumulative labour of generations. Killary Harbour at Leenane is Ireland's only true fjord. Croagh Patrick rising above Westport is climbed by 30,000 pilgrims barefoot on the last Sunday in July ('Reek Sunday').</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>An Spidéal</b> — Gaeltacht (Irish-speaking) seaside village. The pub Tigh Hughes hosts trad sessions you'll remember; the Stiúideo Cuan craft shop displays local makers.</li><li><b>Roundstone</b> — Picture-book village on a sheltered harbour, with the granite hill Errisbeg behind. Roundstone Music makes traditional bodhrán drums.</li><li><b>Sky Road</b> — 12 km loop drive west of Clifden along a high coastal ridge with the Twelve Bens range to the north and the Atlantic spreading out below.</li><li><b>Kylemore Abbey</b> — Neogothic 1868 castle reflected in a lake, now a Benedictine community. The walled Victorian garden is being restored to its original 21-bed plan.</li><li><b>Killary Harbour</b> — 16 km long, only proper fjord in Ireland. Wallace's Maam Cross to Leenane road runs along its south shore. Mussel rafts in the middle; quiet roads either side.</li><li><b>Croagh Patrick</b> — St Patrick's holy mountain (764 m). 30,000 pilgrims climb on Reek Sunday (last Sunday of July), many barefoot. The summit chapel was built in 1905.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
